@node fm_info fm_INFO
                             fm_info

SYNTAX:		fm_info
OPTION:		-

This  command does the same as choosing the INFO menue point.  It
opens  an  info  window  with  then  versions of the soft and the
hardware, free memmory and the @{"copyrights" link copy }.
@endnode


@node fm_quit fm_QUIT
                             fm_quit

SYNTAX:		fm_quit
OPTION:		-

This command does the same as choosing the QUIT menue point.  The
Programm will be terminated.
@endnode


@node fm_init fm_INIT
                             fm_init

SYNTAX:		fm_init
OPTION:		-

This command does the same as choosing the INIT menue Point.  The
config  of  the  Digitizer  will  be sent to the hardware and the
stored  picture  will be lost.  Everytime you switch the hardware
off and on again you have to use fm_init.
@endnode

@node fm_again fm_AGAIN
                            fm_again

SYNTAX:		fm_again
OPTION:		-

This  command  does  the  same as choosing the AGAIN menue point.
the picture in the hardware will be rendered again in exactly the
same resolution an color depth as the last time.  This is usefull
as "redraw".
@endnode

@node fm_palette fm_PALETTE
                           fm_palette

SYNTAX:		fm_palette
OPTION:		-

This  is  the same as choosing the PALETTE menue point.  You will
get  an  REQ  palette requester.  You can load a palette with the
@{"fm_load_palette" link fm_load_palette } commando.
@endnode

@node fm_manipulate fm_MANIPULATE
                           fm_manipulate

SYNTAX:		fm_manipulate
OPTION:		-

This  is  the same as choosing the MANIPULATE menue point.  You will
get a manipulate requester.
@endnode

@node fm_lock_palette fm_LOCK_PALETTE
                           fm_lock_palette

SYNTAX:		fm_lock_palette
OPTION:		-

This  is  the same as choosing the LOCK PALETTE menue point.  You will
get a LOCK requester.  For choosing a palette use the @{"fm_load_palette" link fm_load_palette }
and the @{"fm_palette"link fm_palette } commando
@endnode

@node fm_load_palette fm_LOAD_PALETTE
                         fm_load_palette

SYNTAX:		fm_load_palette ["filename" | ASK]

OPTION:		"FILENAME"	the filename of the palette
		ASK		REQ Filerequester for the filename

This  commando With the ask option it is the same as choosing the
LOAD  PALETTE  menue  point.   With  "filename"  you  can  choose
directly   a   file.    You   can   lock   this  palette  by  the
@{"fm_lock_palette" link fm_lock_palette } commando
@endnode

@node fm_lock fm_LOCK
                             fm_lock

SYNTAX:		fm_lock
OPTION:		-

This  locks all buttons and menues for the user.  They could only
be  reactivated  by  the @{"fm_unlock" link fm_unlock } commando.
@endnode

@node fm_unlock fm_UNLOCK
                            fm_unlock

SYNTAX:		fm_unlock
OPTION:		-

This reactivates all buttons and menues for the user.  they could
be locked by the @{"fm_lock" link fm_lock } commando.
@endnode

@node fm_prefs fm_PREFS
                            fm_prefs

SYNTAX:		fm_prefs [iff "path"] [iff24 "path"] [pri1 x pri2 x]
		         [pal | ntsc] [vcr | tv] [ion | ioff] [save]
		         [prevlo | prevhi] [cvby | yc] [default] [ask]

OPTION:		iff "path"	default path for saving iff`s
		iff24 "path"	default path for saving 24 bit iff`s
		pri1 x pri2 x	cpu use for the menues and the digitizer
		pal | ntsc	choose your tv-system
		vcr | tv	choose if you digitize from vcr or tv-set
		ion | ioff	turns icon creation on and off
		save		saves the preference after changeing it
		prevlo|prevhi	preview in lores or hires
		cvbs | yc	choose the signal type for digitizing
		default		use the default settings
		ask		open the preferences requester

EXAMPEL:	fm_prefs pal vcr yc ion save
		inststalls Framemachine to a pal-yc-vcr videosystem
		switches icon creation on, and saves the preferences.

This  command  is  usefull  when  changing  the  signal  types or
digitizing  from  external  in  diverent formats.
@endnode

@node fm_scr2front fm_SCR2FRONT
                          fm_scr2front

SYNTAX:		fm_scr2front
OPTION:		-

This  command  brings  the  Framemachine  screen  to the top of all
others.   For  dropping  it  back you can use the @{"fm_scr2back"link fm_scr2back }
commando.
@endnode

@node fm_scr2back fm_SCR2BACK
                          fm_scr2back

SYNTAX:		fm_scr2back
OPTION:		-

This  command drops the Framemachine screen behind all others.  For
poping  it up you can use the @{"fm_scr2front"link fm_scr2front } commando.
@endnode

@node fm_new fm_NEW
                             fm_new

SYNTAX:		fm_new [hires] [lace] [oscan] [ntsc] [bw] [2] [4] [8]
		       [16] [32] [64] [4096] [4112] [24b]

OPTION:		hires		switches hires on. default=lores
		lace		switches interlace on. default=nolace
		oscan		switches overscan on. default=no overscan
		ntsc		open an ntsc screen. default=pal
		2...4112	chooses number of colors
		bw		switches to an black&white screen (16 col)
		24b		chooses 24b mode (you get a filerequester

EXAMPEL:	fm_new bw
		open a lores, nolace, no overscan, pal, bw (16 col) screen

		fm_new hires oscan ntsc 16
		opens a hires, nolace, oversan, ntsc, 16 col screen

This commands sets the resolutions if you use the @{"fm_store" link fm_store } commando.
the @{"fm_save" link fm_save } commando will save the screen with the resolutions informations
set with this commando. 
@endnode

@node fm_choose fm_CHOOSE
                            fm_choose

SYNTAX:		fm_choose [titel "blablabla"] [text "blablabla"]

OPTION:		titel		this is the keyword for the text on the top
		text		is the keyword for the showen text

EXAMPELS:	fm_choose titel "arexx message" text "realy delete all ?"
		open a ok/cancel requester with the headline AREXX MESSAGE
		and the text "realy delete all ?". The users reaction will
		bw given back in "result"

see also @{"errorlist" link errorlist } error #1 and #2
@endnode

@node fm_get_err_str fm_GET_ERR_STR
                         fm_get_err_str

SYNTAX:		fm_get_err_str _errornumber

OPTION:		_errornumber	number between 0 and 64

EXAMPEL:	/*litle fm_get_err_str demo*/
		address "Framemachine"
		options results
		buffer = 3
		fm_get_err_str buffer
		buffer = result
		say buffer

		this will bring back EXIT_ERROR on your screen

This command converts a simpel number (can be the result of a arexx command)
into a readabel errorstring.

see also @{"errorlist" link errorlist } collumn NUMBER , SYMBOL
@endnode

@node fm_handel_error fm_HANDEL_ERROR
                         fm_handel_error

SYNTAX:		fm_handel_error _errornumber

OPTION:		_errornumber	number between 0 and 64

EXAMPEL:	/*litle fm_handel_error demo*/
		address "Framemachine"
		options results
		buffer = 5
		fm_handel_error buffer
		
		this will open a requester witch shows OUT OF MEMORY

This  command  us  very  usefull  when  a  arexx command fails to
operate,  because the programm reacts, as choosen a function from
a menue.

see also @{"errorlist" link errorlist }
@endnode

@node fm_store fm_STORE
                            fm_store

SYNTAX:		fm_store
OPTION:		-

This  command  stops  the  online  sampling  of  the  picture and
convetrts it to the requested screen mode. (see also @{"fm_new" link fm_new} )

DANGER!  if there is already a picture in the hardware stored, it
         will be overwritten by the new one!

note: this command syncs the video new
@endnode

@node fm_preview fm_PREVIEW
                           fm_preview

SYNTAX:		fm_preview [noask]

OPTION:		noask		this option switches the resolution
				requester off. so if you press the LMB
				there is no CHOOSE SCREEN.....

This  command  is  good  if  you  like  to  have a preview fom an
external programm, and no one should see the Framemachine GUI.

note: this command syncs the video new
@endnode

@node fm_screen fm_SCREEN
                            fm_screen

SYNTAX:		fm_screen [hires] [lace] [oscan] [ntsc] [bw] [2] [4] [8]
		       [16] [32] [64] [4096] [4112] [24b]

OPTION:		hires		switches hires on. default=lores
		lace		switches interlace on. default=nolace
		oscan		switches overscan on. default=no overscan
		ntsc		open an ntsc screen. default=pal
		2...4112	chooses number of colors
		bw		switches to an black&white screen (16 col)
		24b		this selects 24 bit (you get a filerequester)
		
EXAMPEL:	fm_screen bw
		digitizes  a  lores, nolace, no overscan, pal, bw
		(16 col) screen

		fm_screen hires oscan ntsc 16
		digitizes a hires, nolace, oversan, ntsc,
		16 col screen.

note:  this command doesn`t store a new picture, it only converts
       the picture in the hardware new.
       for the 24b option also see the @{"fm_iff24" link fm_iff24 } commando.
@endnode

@node fm_iff24 fm_IFF24
                            fm_iff24

SYNTAX:		fm_iff24 [hires] [lace] [oscan] [ntsc] [bw] [ask]
		         [fname "filename"]

OPTION:		hires		switches hires on. default=lores
		lace		switches interlace on. default=nolace
		oscan		switches overscan on. default=no overscan
		ntsc		open an ntsc file. default=pal
		bw		switches to an black&white (256 col)
		ask		open an REQ filerequester for the filename
		fname 		this is the keyword for the "filename"

This option was designed to save a 24 bit image without getting a
filerquester like in the @{"fm_screen" link fm_screen } commando.
@endnode

@node fm_save fm_SAVE
                             fm_save

SYNTAX:		fm_save ["filename"] [ask]

OPTION:		"filename"	the filename of the file
		ask		opens a REQ Filerequester for the filename

this option saves the curent screen as IFF/ILBM
@endnode

